Stage 1 of the steno compiler: turns raw `.steno` source text into a `Vec<Entry>`, each entry carrying a stroke key, directive flags, and a parsed template AST (`Vec<Chunk>`). This is the sole producer of `Entry`/`Chunk`/`Expr`/`EntryFlags` — every downstream compiler stage (movement/count expansion, JSON emission) consumes these types as defined here and matches on `Chunk` variants exactly as this subtree produces them.

`mod.rs` owns the shared AST (`Entry`, `Chunk`, `Expr`, `EntryFlags`) and is otherwise inert; `source.rs` walks the file structure (fenced stroke blocks + `@`-directive lines) and calls into `template.rs` once per fenced block to parse the body; `template.rs` in turn calls into `expr.rs` for `%(EXPR)` substrings. The call chain is strictly one-directional: `source.rs` → `template.rs` → `expr.rs`, each handing the next a raw substring and a line number for error tagging.

Two cross-file contracts matter for edits. First, `EntryFlags::set_named` (in `mod.rs`) is the single source of truth for valid `@`-directive names — `source.rs` calls it but never validates names itself, so adding a directive means editing `mod.rs`'s match arm, not `source.rs`. Second, `Chunk`'s variant set is defined in `mod.rs` but every variant is produced only in `template.rs` (with `Repeat`'s body/sep built from nested `parse_template`-style scanning and `Computed` built from `expr.rs`'s output) — adding a new `%`-operator requires a new `Chunk` variant in `mod.rs` and a matching case in `template.rs`'s operator dispatch, plus `kind_name()` staying in sync.

Line-number bookkeeping spans `source.rs` and `template.rs`: `source.rs` computes the 1-based starting line of each fenced block and passes it into `parse_template`, which uses it only to tag error messages (columns are computed locally). Errors are reported at the fence-open/directive line, not the internal offending line, and all index arithmetic uses `saturating_add` to avoid panics on edge-case input. Neither `source.rs` nor `template.rs` ever panics on malformed input — malformed syntax always becomes a `StenoError`, and `expr.rs`'s `parse_expr` similarly returns `None` rather than panicking, which `template.rs` converts into a `StenoError`.